                id = "1", speaker = "The Last Worshipper",
                text = "*(He prays a moment longer, then speaks to you over his shoulder, never turning, the dying sounds punctuating his words.)* You think it's *cowardice.* That I *can't bear* to *watch.* *(a thin, fierce sound.)* You're *wrong*, or — *half* wrong. *(he grips the altar.)* Listen. My god is the *least* of gods. A *small* one. *Patron of thresholds*, of *doorways*, of the *moment between leaving and arriving* — you've *never heard his name*, no one has, he had *one* temple and *one* priest, and you're *looking* at the priest. *(the dying light flickers behind him.)* And the *theology*, stranger — here is the *theology* — a god *lives* by *worship.* That's not *metaphor*, not *this* night. *This* night it is *literal.* The gods are *mortal*, *dying*, and what *keeps* a god is the *belief aimed at it.* *(his voice drops to ferocity.)* So if I *turn around* — if I *look* — I *confirm* it. I make myself a *witness to his death*, and a *witness* believes *\"my god is dying,\" * and that belief *aimed at him* is the *last push* into the *dark.* *(he prays harder.)* But if I *don't* look — if I keep my eyes on the *altar* and *believe, with everything I have, that he is still my living god* — then *some* corner of him, the corner *my* faith is *pointed at*, is *still alive.* *(quietly, desperately.)* I am not *refusing to watch him die.* I am *the only thing keeping him from being dead.* My *not-looking* is the *last wall* between him and the *nothing.* Do you *see?* I *cannot* turn around. I am *load-bearing.*",
