                text = "*(His rigid shoulders shake, and for the first time his voice breaks — but he does *not* turn, and the not-turning is suddenly the bravest thing in the room.)* ...The believer who never looks. *(barely audible over his own prayer.)* Yes. *Yes.* You're the *first* — everyone *else* who's come through that door has *tried to be kind*, tried to *turn me around*, *\"say goodbye, old man, let him go, it's time\"* — and they *don't understand* that their *kindness* is a *knife*, that every *\"let him go\"* is a *push*, that *grief itself* is what *kills* the small gods, the *acceptance*, the *looking-at-the-death-and-believing-it.* *(he presses his forehead to the altar.)* I will *not* give him that. I will *not* let my *love* curdle into the *grief* that *finishes* him. *(fiercely, weeping, facing forward.)* As long as *one* mind in all the world holds him as *living* — *unlooked-at*, *unconfirmed*, *unburied* — he is not *dead*, he is only *dying*, and *dying* is not *death*, *dying* can go on *forever* if no one *agrees* to its *end.* *(quietly.)* I am old, stranger. I will kneel here until *my* heart stops. And in *that* moment — the moment *I* die *still believing* — he and I will cross the *threshold* together, *neither* of us ever having *looked*, and his *patronage* will be *true* to the very *last*: a god of the *in-between*, kept *in-between*, *forever*, by a priest who *refused* to let the door *close.* *(he resumes praying.)* You called it *love.* No one else did. Thank you. *Now let me hold the wall.*",
