                text = "*(He goes utterly still, and the dying sounds behind him seem, for a moment, to quiet, as though the god too is listening.)* Walk through it *with* him. *(slowly.)* His *last rite.* *(his voice fills with a terrible wonder.)* I have been *guarding the door.* *Barring* it. Treating the *threshold* as a thing to *hold shut.* And he is the *god of thresholds* — and I have *forgotten*, in *thirty years* of *keeping* him, that to *Aubrin* a threshold was *never* a thing to *bar.* It was a thing to *cross.* The *holy* moment was *always* the *stepping-through*, the *leaving-and-arriving*, the *in-between* — and I have made his *altar* into a *locked gate*, which is the *one* thing his *whole* divinity was *against.* *(his hands open on the altar.)* I have been *worshipping* him *wrong.* At the very *end.* Guarding him like a *miser* guards *coin*, when he was a god of *passage*, of *release*, of the *grace* of *moving on.* *(a sound that is half sob, half revelation.)* His *last rite* — the *truest* one — is for his *priest* to *take his hand* and *cross with him.* Not to *bar* the threshold. To *be* the *threshold* — the *company* in the *crossing*, the *with* in the *in-between.* *(quietly, beginning, at last, to turn.)* You've given me back my *own* god's *meaning* in the *final* hour. He is not a *wall* to *hold.* He is a *door* to *walk through.* *Together.* *(softly.)* Stay, stranger. Witness a *threshold-god* cross his *last threshold* — *accompanied*, as he always taught, *as I almost forgot.*)",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.worshipper_threshold", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act4.crossed_together", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act1.mercy_remembered", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 5 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "leave", speaker = "The Last Worshipper",
                text = "*(He shakes his head violently, facing the altar, and his prayer rises to drown you out.)* No. *No.* I don't *want* your *understanding*, I don't want it *named*, I don't want it made *beautiful* or *brave* or *anything* — naming it makes me *think* about it, and *thinking* about it is *one step* from *looking*, and *looking* is the *end.* *(he prays louder.)* Go. *Please.* You seem *kind*, and *kind* is *dangerous* to me right now, kind is what *turns priests around.* I have *thirty years* of *not-looking* to protect and a *handful of minutes* left to *do* it in. *(his voice cracks.)* Let me hold the wall in *silence.* Let me be a *fool* who *prays to a dying god's back* if that's what I *am.* It's *mine* to be. *(and he kneels, rigid, facing forward, the last worshipper of a small dead god, holding the only wall he has with the whole of his failing heart.)*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "close", speaker = "The Last Worshipper",
                text = "*(The last worshipper kneels at the altar with his back to the death — praying his small god into one more moment of not-quite-dead by the sheer force of refusing to look — and whether he held the wall to the end, shared the watch, or finally turned to walk his threshold-god through its last threshold, you carry away the most intimate faith of the whole god-fall: that a thing is only fully dead when the last one who loves it *agrees* — and that somewhere, always, there is one stubborn heart that simply *will not.*)*",
            });

            NpcTroublesWorshipperDialogue = g;
        }
    }
